body: Oh after Ctrl+D to kill the process, the terminal prints "error: overflow evaluating the requirement `_ : core::marker::Sized` [E0275]" now, but still hang after printing "error: aborting due to previous error"

Got 

```
sexp/lib.rs:1:1: 1:1 error: overflow evaluating the requirement `_ : core::marker::Sized` [E0275]
sexp/lib.rs:1 use std::iter::Peekable;
```

after a few minutes of trans (and an exhausted randomness pool). 

(1284be404 2015-04-18 on linux)

Maybe it's because my `./configure --enable-debug --enable-optimize`, and per https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/24601 it's probably a Windows-only thing (I'd admit it's likely that these are 2 different things).

I'm using Windows 8.1 64 bit.

I tested `rustc 1.0.0-nightly (00978a987 2015-04-18) (built 2015-04-19)` resulted in

```
real    2m41.611s
user    0m0.000s
sys     0m0.030s
```

(it seems that "-Z time-passes" is not useful in this case)

Okay my local rustc take 10 minutes to compile now.

```
real    9m5.706s
user    0m0.000s
sys     0m0.015s
```

The thing is, last time I tried I was using a rustc without `--enable-optimize` (see https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/24405), so rustc didn't make it to compile within 1 hour.

_**edit:**_ fixed a miss-copy&paste
FWIW: removing the `main()` makes the error go away.
